Evaluating regression models

  • Split the data into 6 parts and shuffle 42 times.
  • Here use 4 different models (Linear Regression, KNeighbors Regressor, Decision Tree Regressor and Random Forest Regressor)
  • 6 folds of accuracy, mean, standard deviation for 3 models for choose the best model.
  • Decision Tree Classifier is the best model because is has the highest accuracy.
In [ ]:
#**Cross-Validation Performance**
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, KFold
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

kf = KFold(n_splits=6, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

# Cross-validation performance of Linear Regression
print('Cross-validation performance of Linear Regression')

print(f'6 folds of R² scores: {cv_results_lin_reg}')
print('Mean & standard deviation of R² score for all 6 folds:')
print(np.mean(cv_results_lin_reg), np.std(cv_results_lin_reg))
print('The 2.5th percentile and 97.5th percentile of R² scores:')
print(np.quantile(cv_results_lin_reg, [0.025, 0.975])) # We can 95% confident that the true performance of Linear Regression model on new, unseen data lies between approximately 2.5th percentile and 97.5th percentile)

Preprocessing

  • Create pipelines for standardization purpose for big range in numerical features.
In [ ]:
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

# Create preprocessing pipelines
standardscaler_pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())
])

df_cleaned_features = ['bedrooms', 'sqft_living', 'sqft_lot', 'floors', 'view', 'condition', 'lat', 'long', 'sqft_lot15', 'house_age']

# Use ColumnTransformer to apply preprocessing pipelines to the correct columns
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num_standardscaler_transform', standardscaler_pipeline, df_cleaned_features)
    ],
    remainder='drop' # Any columns in dataset that are not explicitly mentioned in the transformers list will be dropped.
)

# Integrate into a full pipeline with RandomForestRegressor model.
ranforreg_full_pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('random_forest_regressor', RandomForestRegressor())
])

Hyperparameter tuning (GridSearchCV)¶

RandomForestRegressor

  • Find the best parameter for the best model (Random Forest Regressor)
In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

param_grid_ran_for_reg = {
    'random_forest_regressor__n_estimators': [50, 100],
    'random_forest_regressor__max_depth': [10, 20],
    'random_forest_regressor__min_samples_split': [2, 4],
    'random_forest_regressor__min_samples_leaf': [1, 2]
}

grid_search_ran_for_reg = GridSearchCV(ranforreg_full_pipeline, param_grid_ran_for_reg, cv=4)
grid_search_ran_for_reg.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(f'Best parameters of Random Forest Regressor: {grid_search_ran_for_reg.best_params_}')
print(f'Best cross-validation accuracy for Random Forest Regressor: {grid_search_ran_for_reg.best_score_:.3f}') # with best combination of hyperparameters

r_squared_ran_for_reg = grid_search_ran_for_reg.score(X_test, y_test)
print(f'R-squared of Random Forest Regressor:{r_squared_ran_for_reg: .4f}')

y_pred_ran_for_reg = grid_search_ran_for_reg.predict(X_test)
mse_ran_for_reg = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_ran_for_reg)
rmse_ran_for_reg = np.sqrt(mse_ran_for_reg)

print(f'RMSE of Random Forest Regressor: {rmse_ran_for_reg: .4f}')

Baseline

  • Use baseline to compare with best model (Random Forest Regressor).
  • The R-squared of Random Forest Regressor (0.8742) is better than accuracy of baseline (-0.0001) because closer to 1.
  • The RMSE of Random Forest Regressor (140599.3239) is better than baseline (399035.93) because Random Forest Regressor value is smaller.

    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('dummy_regressor', DummyRegressor())
])

rmse_dummy = np.sqrt(mse_dummy)  # squared=False in mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred, squared=False) is unable to use

Conclusion

  • Random Forest Regressor is the best model for predicting 'price'.
  • It shows a clear improvement when compare with evaluate cross-validation peformance and simple baseline.
  • Too many irrelevant features can cause the noise and degrade the performance.
  • Overfitting and underfitting in the parameter grid can cause errors in the system.
